'''Haji Amir Wright''' (born March 27, 1998) is an American professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for {{English football updater|CoventrC}} club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

After making his professional debut with the [[New York Cosmos (2013–2020)|New York Cosmos]] in 2015, he has spent most of his career in Europe, with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in the German [[Bundesliga]], [[VVV-Venlo]] in the Dutch [[Eredivisie]], [[SønderjyskE Fodbold|SønderjyskE]] in the [[Danish Superliga]] and [[Antalyaspor]] in the Turkish [[Süper Lig]].

Wright made his senior debut for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] in 2022 and played at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].

==Youth soccer==
Known for his finishing, ability to win headers, and quickness,<ref>{{cite web|title=LA Galaxy's Haji Wright leads list of 7 MLS Academy players called to US U-17 national team|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/04/01/la-galaxys-haji-wright-leads-list-7-mls-academy-players-called-us-under-17-n|website=MLS Soccer|publisher=MLSSoccer.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015|date=April 1, 2014|archive-date=June 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624010145/http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/04/01/la-galaxys-haji-wright-leads-list-7-mls-academy-players-called-us-under-17-n|url-status=dead}}</ref> Wright was dubbed by many media outlets as one of the top prospects in the United States youth system.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Noah|title=Haji Wright and the Next Big Thing: Should the USMNT Be Getting More From Its Under-17 Team?|url=http://grantland.com/the-triangle/usmnt-u17-haji-wright-development/|website=Grantland|publisher=Grantland.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015|date=February 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Wright stuff for USA?|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/y=2015/m=2/news=the-wright-stuff-for-usa-2534249.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302040718/http://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/news/y=2015/m=2/news=the-wright-stuff-for-usa-2534249.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 2, 2015|website=FIFA|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> His success with the under-17 national team prompted him to train with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]'s academy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parchman|first1=Will|title=Haji Wright on the precipice of Europe|url=http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/club-soccer-articles/haji-wright-on-the-precipice-of-europe_aid32303|website=Top Drawer Soccer|publisher=TopDrawerSoccer.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref>

==Club career==
=== New York Cosmos ===
In March 2015, Wright officially signed with [[North American Soccer League (2011–2017)|NASL]] club [[New York Cosmos (2013–2020)|New York Cosmos]] for an undisclosed fee and contract length.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cosmos Sign Striker Haji Wright|url=http://www.nycosmos.com/news/2015/03/30/cosmos-sign-striker-haji-wright|website=New York Cosmos|publisher=NYCosmos.com}}</ref> He made his professional debut on May 27 in the third round of the [[U.S. Open Cup]], as a 79th-minute substitute for [[Sebastián Guenzatti]] in a 3–0 home win over the [[Jersey Express S.C.|Jersey Express]], and then played three league games for a total of 80 minutes, starting with the game versus [[Indy Eleven]] on July 26.<ref>{{Soccerway|haji-wright/401946|Haji Wright}}</ref> Wright's contract expired following the season, and he did not re-sign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycosmos.com/news/2015/12/03/cosmos-announce-first-roster-moves-following-championship-2015-season|title=Cosmos Announce First Roster Moves Following Championship 2015 Season|publisher=New York Cosmos}}</ref>

=== Schalke 04 ===
In April 2016, Wright signed with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schalke04.de/de/aktuell/news/160415_wright/page/7636--10-213-.html|title=Spielberechtigung für Haji Wright ist da|publisher=schalke04.de|language=German|date=April 16, 2016|access-date=April 16, 2016|archive-date=August 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811222209/http://www.schalke04.de/de/aktuell/news/160415_wright/page/7636--10-213-.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In his debut with the Schalke under-19 team on April 16, Wright scored a brace against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] U19.

Wright was promoted to the Schalke first team in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/schalke-promote-american-duo-weston-mckennie-and-haji-wright-to-senior-squad-444638.jsp|title=Schalke promote American duo McKennie and Wright to senior squad|website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website|access-date=May 20, 2017|archive-date=March 29, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220329124221/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/schalke-promote-american-duo-weston-mckennie-and-haji-wright-to-senior-squad-444638.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was named on the bench against [[FC Ingolstadt 04]] on May 20, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/05/20/germany/bundesliga/fc-ingolstadt-04/fc-schalke-04/2255209/|title=Ingolstadt vs. Schalke 04 – 20 May 2017 – Soccerway|website=uk.soccerway.com}}</ref> In July 2018, Wright underwent a trial period with [[2. Bundesliga]] club [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Haji Wright trains with Union first-team |url=https://www.fc-union-berlin.de/en/union-live/latest-news/professional/Haji-Wright-trains-with-Union-first-team-116u/|website=1. FC Union Berlin|date=July 10, 2018|accessdate=May 3, 2019}}</ref> On November 24, 2018, Wright made his debut for Schalke first team when he replaced [[Steven Skrzybski]] in the 88th minute of the 5–2 win against [[1. FC Nürnberg]].<ref name="Schalke 04 vs. Nürnberg 5 - 2">{{cite web |title=Schalke 04 vs. Nürnberg 5 – 2 |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/11/24/germany/bundesliga/fc-schalke-04/1-fc-nurnberg/2811009/?ICID=PL_MS_08 |website=Soccerway |accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref> He played seven games for the team from [[Gelsenkirchen]], all in the league, and scored a consolation goal in a 2–1 home loss to [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] on December 19; the goal was assisted by compatriot [[Weston McKennie]].<ref>{{cite news |title=American Haji Wright nets first goal for Schalke |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/haji-wright-scores-first-goal-for-schalke-from-weston-mckennie-assist-usa-usmnt-1010 |access-date=December 21, 2022 |publisher=Bundesliga |date=December 19, 2018}}</ref>

=== VVV-Venlo ===
In July 2019, Wright joined [[VVV-Venlo]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/en/team/haji-wright-joins-vvv-venlo/|title=Haji Wright joins VVV Venlo|publisher=Schalke 04|date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> He played 22 [[Eredivisie]] games without scoring, but scored in the first round of the [[KNVB Cup]] on October 30; coming on in the last minute, he tied the game at 2–2 at fourth-tier [[RKSV Groene Ster]], but missed the decisive attempt in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] defeat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amateurs Groene Ster zorgen voor enorme stunt tegen eredivisionist VVV|trans-title=Amateurs Groene Ster provide a huge shock against Eredivisie team VVV |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2308361-amateurs-groene-ster-zorgen-voor-enorme-stunt-tegen-eredivisionist-vvv |access-date=December 21, 2022 |publisher=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=October 30, 2019 |language=Dutch}}</ref>

=== SønderjyskE ===
In August 2020, Wright joined [[SønderjyskE Fodbold|SønderjyskE]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Henry jr. |first1=Larry |title=Haji Wright joins Danish Superliga side Sonderjyske |url=https://sbisoccer.com/2020/08/haji-wright-joins-danish-superliga-side-sonderjyske |access-date=December 1, 2020 |work=SBI Soccer |date=August 2, 2020}}</ref> He got off to a strong start in the league, with six goals in eight appearances by early November, and his performances led to him being named as the [[Danish Superliga]] Player of the Month for October 2020.<ref name="potm-1020" />

In July 2021, Wright wanted to move on from SønderjyskE and failed to report back for pre-season training.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/se-direktoer-om-wright-gaar-imod-trup-og-stab/|title=SE-direktør om Wright: Går imod trup og stab|publisher=bold.dk|date=July 20, 2021}}</ref> On July 21, Turkish club [[Antalyaspor]] confirmed that they had signed Wright on loan from SønderjyskE with an option to buy.<ref>[https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/bekraeftet-tyrkisk-klub-lejer-ses-haji-wright/ Bekræftet: Tyrkisk klub lejer SE's Haji Wright], bold.dk, July 21, 2021</ref> However, later on the same day, SønderjyskE went out and denied that the deal had gone through because they had not yet received any payment.<ref>[https://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/se-er-uenig-wright-handel-er-ikke-paa-plads/ SE er uenig: Wright-handel er ikke på plads], bold.dk, July 21, 2021</ref> However, on July 28, SønderjyskE confirmed that he had been loaned out to Antalyaspor for the 2021–22 season and also signed a new deal with Sønderjyske until June 2024.<ref>[https://soenderjyske.dk/fodbold/soenderjyske-forlaenger-og-udlejer-haji-wright/ SØNDERJYSKE FORLÆNGER OG UDLEJER HAJI WRIGHT], soenderjyske.dk, July 28, 2021</ref>

=== Antalyaspor ===
Wright opened his account for Antalyaspor in his third game on August 28, 2021, in which he scored a [[hat-trick]] in a 3–2 home win over [[Çaykur Rizespor]], concluding with a penalty kick in the tenth minute of added time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galarcep |first1=Ives |title=Haji Wright's stoppage-time winner completes hat-trick for Antalyaspor |url=https://sbisoccer.com/2021/08/haji-wrights-stoppage-time-winner-completes-hat-trick-for-antalyaspor |access-date=December 21, 2022 |work=SBI Soccer |date=August 29, 2021}}</ref> He scored 14 goals in 31 games in the [[2021–22 Süper Lig]], including eight over seven consecutive games, and nine in the last ten games.

On July 19, 2022, Wright signed for Antalyaspor permanently on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/national/story/2022-07-19/haji-wright-transfers-to-antalyaspor-gets-3-year-deal | title=Haji Wright transfers to Antalyaspor, gets 3-year deal |work=San Diego Tribune|date=July 19, 2022 }}</ref> He scored 16 goals in all competitions for the club as they finished 13th in the Süper Lig.<ref>{{Cite web |title=2022–2023 Sezonu Spor Toto Süper Lig Fikstürü ve Puan Cetveli TFF |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=1628 |access-date=2024-08-20 |website=www.tff.org}}</ref>

=== Coventry City ===
Wright joined [[EFL Championship]] club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] on August 4, 2023, on a four-year contract for a club-record transfer fee of €9 million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=TRANSFER: Haji Wright joins Coventry City|url=https://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/2023/august/transfer-haji-wright-joins-coventry-city|website=ccfc.co.uk}}</ref> On August 12, 2023, he scored his first goal for the club on his home debut in a 3–0 win against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Sky Blues brush Boro aside despite Hamer departure |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66413374 |access-date=2023-08-12 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On March 16, 2024, Wright converted a 100th minute stoppage time goal for Coventry in the quarter-finals of the [[2023–24 FA Cup]] against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], helping the club progress beyond the round for the first time since Coventry's [[1986–87 FA Cup]] victory.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stone |first=Simon |date=2024-03-16 |title=Wolves 2–3 Coventry: Haji Wright scores 100th-minute winner in FA Cup classic |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68573287 |access-date=2024-03-16 |work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> In the semi-final against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] Wright scored a 95th minute equalizing penalty to complete a comeback from 3–0 down and take the game to extra time. He then provided an assist for a 121st minute goal by [[Victor Torp]], but this was disallowed by VAR for offside and Coventry were eliminated on penalties.<ref>{{Cite news|date=2024-04-20|title=FA Cup semi-final: Man Utd survive stunning Coventry comeback to win on penalties |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/68650698 |access-date=2024-08-20 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He finished the 2023–24 season with 19 goals in all competitions, including 16 in the Championship.<ref name=":0" />

Wright scored his first goals of the 2024–25 season against [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] in a 3–2 win on August 16, including an injury time winner after an error by [[Will Vaulks]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coventry score 96th-minute winner against Oxford Utd |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c5ylvpydxk4t |access-date=2024-08-20 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> During a 2–2 draw against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on November 9, Wright picked up an ankle ligament injury, which kept him out of action for four months.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sky Blues striker Wright to miss Sheff Utd game
|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c5ygzrv1qvno |access-date= 2025-03-16 |website=BBC Sport |date=November 22, 2024 |language=en-GB}}</ref> On March 15, Wright scored a hat-trick against Sunderland in a 3–0 victory for Coventry, these were his first goals since returning from injury, and it was also his first hat-trick for the club.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wright hat-trick for Coventry sinks Sunderland
|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cqjdgr5jlgxt |access-date= 2025-03-16 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He scored a second hat-trick on February 16, 2026 in a crucial 3–1 home win over Middlesbrough.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cze03ypy54et</ref>

==International career==
[[File:U.S.-Wales Men’s World Cup Match in Doha, Qatar. (52515715639).jpg|thumb|Wright (in white) playing against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]
Wright is of Liberian and Ghanaian descent. He has represented the [[United States national men's soccer team|United States]] at all levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://liberiapublicradio.com/2021/02/21/sonderjyske-rejects-e1-3m-bid-from-malmo-ff-for-american-liberian-haji-wright/|title=SønderjyskE Rejects €1.3m Bid From Malmo FF for American-Liberian Haji Wright &#124; Liberia Public Radio|date=February 21, 2021 }}</ref> In May 2022, Wright was called into the United States senior camp by [[Gregg Berhalter]] for a [[2022–23 CONCACAF Nations League|CONCACAF Nations League]] window.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Berhalter Calls 27 Players For June Training Camp And Final Home Matches Before 2022 FIFA World Cup |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2022/05/berhalter-calls-27-players-for-june-training-camp-and-final-home-matches-before-2022-fifa-world-cup |access-date=May 23, 2022 |website=ussoccer.com |language=en}}</ref>

Wright scored his first international goal on his senior debut for the United States on June 1, 2022, in a 3–0 friendly victory against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ussoccer.com/competitions/usmnt-friendlies-2022/matches/united-states-vs-morocco-6-1-2022 | title=United States vs Morocco }}</ref> In November 2022, Wright was named to the squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2022/11/berhalter-names-26-player-usmnt-roster-for-2022-fifa-world-cup|title=Berhalter Names 26 Player USMNT Roster For 2022 FIFA World Cup|website=ussoccer.com}}</ref> He scored for the United States in their 3–1 loss to the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |title='Can't tell if lucky or intentional': US star scores 'accidentally excellent' goal that defies physics |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/world-cup/cant-tell-if-lucky-or-intentional-us-star-scores-accidentally-excellent-goal-that-defies-physics/news-story/5b33ce8c6fbea88db8bdad18f638a1b9 |access-date=December 21, 2022 |work=Fox Sports |date=December 4, 2022}}</ref>

On March 17, 2024, Wright was called up to the national team as an injury replacement for [[Josh Sargent]] to compete in the [[2024 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-13 |title=BRENDEN AARONSON AND HAJI WRIGHT ADDED TO USMNT ROSTER FOR 2024 CONCACAF NATIONS LEAGUE FINALS |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2024/03/brenden-aaronson-and-haji-wright-added-to-usmnt-roster-for-2024-concacaf-nations-league-finals |access-date=2024-03-22 |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]]}}</ref> On March 21, he scored an extra-time brace against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-22 |title=U.S. MEN'S NATIONAL TEAM ADVANCES TO 2024 CONCACAF NATIONS LEAGUE FINAL WITH 3–1 SEMIFINAL WIN OVER JAMAICA |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2024/03/concacaf-nations-league-semifinal-usmnt-vs-jamaica-result-score-match-recap-stats-goals |access-date=2024-03-22 |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Haji's brother Hanif played on the under-19 team of [[Bonner SC]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beinsports.com/us/americans-overseas/news/americans-overseas-january-transfer-triumph/453303|title=Americans Overseas: January Transfer Triumph|date=February 14, 2017 |website=[[BeIN Sports]]}}</ref> Haji's cousins are also active in athletics: Joseph Putu played [[cornerback]] for the [[Florida Gators football|Florida Gators]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seccountry.com/florida/joseph-putu-a-war-refugee-for-six-years-overcame-all-odds-to-reach-florida|title=Joseph Putu, a war refugee for six years, overcame long odds to reach Florida|website=SecCountry.com}}</ref> his second cousin, Isaac Nana Addai, played for the [[Liberia national under-23 football team|Liberia national under-23 team]] as well as [[Boston City FC]], and his third cousin, [[Joseph Addai]], won [[Super Bowl XLI]] in 2007 with the [[Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.santaclarabroncos.com/sports/m-soccer/2016-17/releases/20170207o98s3w|title=Addai comes from a very athletic family including his cousin, Joseph Addai, an NFL running back and Super Bowl winner. Haji Wright|website=[[Santa Clara Broncos]]|date=February 7, 2017|access-date=February 16, 2018|archive-date=June 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619214342/https://www.santaclarabroncos.com/sports/m-soccer/2016-17/releases/20170207o98s3w|url-status=dead}}</ref>

